In 152 countries worldwide. To study as much of the world as possible across the entire time series (1961-2009), we standardized areas that changed over the past 50 years, for example by recombining the countries formerly in the the USSR and Yugoslavia

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section][et_pb_section admin_label="Section" fullwidth="off" specialty="off"][et_pb_row admin_label="Row"][et_pb_column type="4_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Text" background_layout="light" text_orientation="center" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]

And found dramatic change

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row admin_label="Row"][et_pb_column type="1_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Text" background_layout="light" text_orientation="justified" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]

National diets grew larger and richer. On average, countries’ food supplies from both plant and animal sources consistently increased over the past 50 years in terms of calories, protein, fat, and food weight. Oils as a food group showed some of the most dramatic increases

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row admin_label="Row"][et_pb_column type="3_4"][et_pb_code admin_label="Code"]<div class="tableauPlaceholder" id="viz1479363348593" style="margin-left:13%;padding:1px 16px;height:755px;"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <noscript><a href="#"><img alt="The Changing Global Diet " src="https://public.tableau.com/static/images/St/Story6_GlobalRichness/6_GlobalRich/1_rss.png" style="border: none"></a></noscript><object class="tableauViz" style="display:none;"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="host_url" value="https%3A%2F%2Fpublic.tableau.com%2F"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="site_root" value=""><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="name" value="Story6_GlobalRichness/6_GlobalRich"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="tabs" value="no"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="toolbar" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="static_image" value="https://public.tableau.com/static/images/St/Story6_GlobalRichness/6_GlobalRich/1.png"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="animate_transition" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_static_image" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_spinner" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_overlay" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_count" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> </object><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> </div><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <script type="text/javascript"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> var divElement = document.getElementById("viz1479363348593"); Countries’ food supplies added an average of 9 new crop commodities contributing to calories, 6 to protein, 5 to fat, and 10 to food weight

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section][et_pb_section admin_label="Section" fullwidth="off" specialty="off"][et_pb_row admin_label="Row"][et_pb_column type="4_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Text" background_layout="light" text_orientation="center" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]

National diets became more even

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row admin_label="Row"][et_pb_column type="1_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Text" background_layout="light" text_orientation="justified" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]

Countries’ food supplies increased in evenness, indicating greater equality in the relative importance of each of the crop commodities contributing to food supplies within each country

The evenness scale refers to Pielou’s Evenness Index, where 0 is a diet totally dominated by a single food, and 1 is a diet where all foods contribute an equal amount

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="3_4"][et_pb_code admin_label="Code"]<div class="tableauPlaceholder" id="viz1479363786227" style="margin-left:13%;padding:1px 16px;height:755px;"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <noscript><a href="#"><img alt="The Changing Global Diet " src="https://public.tableau.com/static/images/St/Story8_GlobalEvenness/8_GlobalEven/1_rss.png" style="border: none"></a></noscript><object class="tableauViz" style="display:none;"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="host_url" value="https%3A%2F%2Fpublic.tableau.com%2F"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="site_root" value=""><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="name" value="Story8_GlobalEvenness/8_GlobalEven"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="tabs" value="no"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="toolbar" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="static_image" value="https://public.tableau.com/static/images/St/Story8_GlobalEvenness/8_GlobalEven/1.png"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="animate_transition" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_static_image" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_spinner" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_overlay" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_count" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> </object><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> </div><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <script type="text/javascript"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> var divElement = document.getElementById("viz1479363786227"); The most dominant foods in national diets became less important

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][et_pb_row admin_label="Row"][et_pb_column type="3_4"][et_pb_code admin_label="Code"]<div class="tableauPlaceholder" id="viz1479364338037" style="margin-left:13%;padding:1px 16px;height:755px;"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <noscript><a href="#"><img alt="The Changing Global Diet " src="https://public.tableau.com/static/images/St/Story10_GlobalDominance/10_GlobalDom/1_rss.png" style="border: none"></a></noscript><object class="tableauViz" style="display:none;"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="host_url" value="https%3A%2F%2Fpublic.tableau.com%2F"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="site_root" value=""><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="name" value="Story10_GlobalDominance/10_GlobalDom"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="tabs" value="no"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="toolbar" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="static_image" value="https://public.tableau.com/static/images/St/Story10_GlobalDominance/10_GlobalDom/1.png"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="animate_transition" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_static_image" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_spinner" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_overlay" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <param name="display_count" value="yes"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> </object><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> </div><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <script type="text/javascript"><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> var divElement = document.getElementById("viz1479364338037"); vizElement.parentNode.insertBefore(scriptElement, vizElement); <!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> </script><!-- [et_pb_line_break_holder] --> <div></div>[/et_pb_code][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_4"][et_pb_text admin_label="Text" background_layout="light" text_orientation="justified" use_border_color="off" border_color="#ffffff" border_style="solid"]

The proportion of countries’ food supplies comprised of the most abundant crop commodity declined on average. Particularly notable reductions in originally very high levels of dominance were visible in rice in contribution to calories in Southeast Asia, coconut for fat in Pacific Island countries, and groundnut for fat in Central African countries

The dominance scale refers to percent contribution to national food supplies by the most important food (whichever it is), where 0 means no contribution to diet, and 1 means 100% contribution to diet

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section]
